<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,508,1110]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">
The nominal form presents yellow and black bands with a white tail. Individuals with a pronounced ferruginous colouring on T4 have been regarded here as the subspecies 
<emphasis box="[1010,1112,581,606]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">lectitatus</emphasis>
(
<tableCitation box="[1132,1224,581,606]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetBox="[159,1394,332,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="TABLE 2. Bumblebee species and subspecies collected in the Pyrenees and IUCN category ranks (from Spain: Verdú &amp; Galante (2006), Verdú et al. (2011) and from Europe: Rasmont et al. (2015): Not Evaluated, NE; Endangered, EN; Vulnerable, VU; Data Deficient, DD; Least Concern, LC) of the extant bumblebee species and subspecies in the Pyrenees. The number of individuals sampled between 2006 and 2015 is indicated. In rare species and those with relevant records, the number of individuals known from historical literature or collections is included in brackets." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BDBE6627FF98FFBFFF3CFF45FADEFED5" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" tableUuid="BDBE6627FF98FFBFFF3CFF45FADEFED5">Table 2</tableCitation>
), considered until recently as the only one spread in the Pyrenees (Rasmont &amp; Iserbyt 2013). This pronounced ferruginous colouring of T4 is constant and differs from that in 
<emphasis box="[633,803,654,677]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">B. s. ancaricus</emphasis>
or 
<emphasis box="[846,990,654,677]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">B. s. proteus</emphasis>
, but further genetic research would be desirable at the subspecies level. This subspecies has been found only in central and eastern Pyrenees, between 
<date box="[151,321,725,750]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" value="1532" valueMax="2125">
1532 and 
<quantity box="[265,321,725,750]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.125" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="2125.0">2125</quantity>
</date>
m, on 
<taxonomicName box="[405,591,726,749]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Cirsium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvense">
